undoubtedly the revolution.

The revolution, the people’s revolution was a positive one.

It was to bring in dignity, justice, peace

and goodness to the Syrian people and I was head of the knowledge transfer and advancement council in the government.

I was stopped behind the scenes from having a dialogue between two scientists in Syria well known in Aleppo and Damascus to run a program that brought in for the first time science technology and universities linkage.

This was the biggest bonehead thing I’ve ever done.

You don’t make science as a category of human beings special.

You make everybody who wants to know something special.

Science is for everybody.

You can ignore it because you don’t understand it.

But in the long run you will have a reaction from society because science is going to take on you.

But I refused to give up on science.

And in 2007 there was a nomad who joined my family.

He came from the deserts of Saudi and he said he kept having visions at night dedicated to demolishing the military entertainment complex.

Before it started happening, Hams let loose his fist and said I’m going to start.

And he called me crazy and I said we’re going through stuff in Syria now.

But 14 years, 14 and a half what’s changed Neohim.

Nothing’s changed, we’ve got big problems.

So now there is no word for “no” in the vocabulary of the Syrian people.

That’s what I’ve been fighting against to this day
